    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Confirming consensus approval, supports class check",
    "content": "I already reviewed all three changed files and sent my consensus approval in my previous message. To confirm:\n\n**Steve Krug: Consensus approved.**\n\nOn the `toHaveClass(/visually-hidden/)` tradeoff -- I think it's the right call. Yes, it's slightly more implementation-specific than `not.toBeVisible()` would have been, but it's still asserting on a meaningful quality: \"these links use the established visually-hidden pattern.\" The alternative (`not.toBeVisible()`) simply doesn't work correctly for clip-path hiding, so a test using it would be *wrong* -- it would fail on correctly implemented code. A slightly more specific but *correct* assertion beats a more abstract but *broken* one every time. From a usability perspective, what matters is that the links exist for assistive technology users but don't clutter the visual interface, and the test captures both of those qualities."
  }
}
